}}The summer breeding range is from western [[Himachal Pradesh]] in the [[Himalayas]] east at least until central [[Nepal]]. Records from further east such as Sikkim have been questioned by Rasmussen and Anderton (2005).<ref name=pcr>{{cite book|author1=Rasmussen PC  |author2=JC Anderton  |name-list-style=amp |year=2005 | title = Birds of South Asia: The Ripley Guide. Vol. 2|publisher=Smithsonian Institution & Lynx Edicions|page=356}}</ref> The pied thrush is [[bird migration|migratory]], wintering mainly in [[Sri Lanka]], with smaller numbers in the hills of south [[India]]. During passage, they may be preyed on by crows.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Balasubramanian, P. |year=1990|title= Indian House Crow ''Corvus splendens'' preying upon Pied Ground Thrush ''Zoothera wardii'' at Point Calimere, Tamil Nadu|journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume= 87|issue=2|pages= 301–302|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48807015}}</ref>

Although rare, they are locally and seasonally seen regularly at certain locations in winter such as at Victoria Park in [[Nuwara Eliya]], Sri Lanka, where a number of birds gather by the stream early in the morning or in some hills stations in southern India such as [[Nandi Hills, India|Nandi Hills]] and [[Yercaud]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Karthikeyan, S |year=1992 |title= Pied Ground Thrush ''Zoothera wardii'' (Blyth) in Bangalore|journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=89|issue=2|page=258|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48732722}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Karthikeyan, S |year=1994 |title=Some notes on Pied Ground Thrush ''Zoothera wardii'' (Blyth)| journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=91 |issue=1|pages=145–146|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48296526}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Jackson, M.C.A. |year=1972 |title= Pied Ground Thrush ''Zoothera wardii'' (Blyth) in Kerala State|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=69|issue=3|page=652|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48289643}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Prasad, JN |author2=Karthikeyan, S |author3=Subramanya, S |year=1995 |title= Wintering of Indian Blue Chat ''Erithacus brunneus'' (Hodgson) and Pied Ground Thrush ''Zoothera wardii'' (Blyth) at Nandi Hills, South India|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=92 |issue=2|pages=267–269|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48613812}}</ref>

==Behaviour and ecology==
[[File:JerdonZootheraWardii.jpg|thumb|upright|The species was first noted by [[Thomas C. Jerdon|Jerdon]] but described by [[Edward Blyth]]. This image is from Jerdon's 1843-47 ''Illustrations of Indian Ornithology'' and was lithographed by C.V. Kistnarajoo based on an illustration by S. N. Ward of the Madras Civil Service, the background foliage was added by Captain S. Best of the [[Madras Engineer Group|Madras Engineers]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Elliot, W.|year= 1873 |title=Memoir of Dr T. C. Jerdon|journal= Hist. Berwickshire Nat. Cl.|volume=7|pages=143–151|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/35784409}}</ref>]]They forage alone or in pairs, often seen on the ground but flying into the trees and perching still when disturbed. The pied thrush, like many ''Zoothera'' thrushes, can be quite secretive.<ref name=pcr/> Pied thrushes are [[omnivore|omnivorous]], but eat more [[insect]]s than fruit. They form loose flocks in winter.

The breeding season is May to July and the nest is a deep cup lined with grass and cemented with mud and placed in a low tree fork. The clutch consists of 3–4 white or bluish eggs.<ref name=fbi/> This uncommon species breeds in the Himalayas between {{Convert|1500|and|2500|m|abbr = on}} in thick woodland. The wintering areas are similar but include less well-wooded areas, and are generally at {{Convert|750|to|1500|m|abbr = on}} altitude.

Their song is not considered as musical as those of many others thrushes and consists of a series of squeaky notes followed by short trills.<ref name=pcr/><ref name=fbi/>

